{"meta":{"domain":"subjects","kid":"5234","authors":[{"fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre","id":"6"}],"title":"","dates":{"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:42 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:42 UTC"}},"nodes":[{"index":0,"parent_index":-1,"body":"<p class=\"Paragraph\">In Literary Tibetan, the adversative connective <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f9f\u0f7a\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cbut\u201d has several variants according to the last letter of the preceding syllable.<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f9f\u0f7a\u0f0b<\/span> is used after <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0f0b<\/span> <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span> <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f0b<\/span> <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f58\u0f0b<\/span> <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f0b<\/span> and vowels <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f7a\u0f0b<\/span> is used after <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f0b<\/span><\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f4f\u0f7a\u0f0b<\/span> is used after <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span> <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f62\u0f0b<\/span> <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span> <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> and the <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f51\u0fb2\u0f42\u0f0b<\/span><\/li> <\/ul><p class=\"Paragraph\">In speech, the three are all pronounced <em>de<\/em>.<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">This particle has a range of functions in Literary Tibetan. In the spoken language, by contrast, it is used only to introduce an opposition between two phrases or a concession, and may be translated by \u201cbut\u201d or \u201calthough.\u201d<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">The particle <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f9f\u0f7a\u0f0b<\/span> is only used after certain auxiliaries. It usually appears in the following combinations: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f61\u0f7c\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f7a\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f61\u0f7c\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f7a\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f7a\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f51\u0f74\u0f42\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f9f\u0f7a\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f61\u0f72\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f4f\u0f7a\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f62\u0f7a\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f4f\u0f7a\u0f0b<\/span>.<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f51\u0fb2\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f7c\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f7a\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f45\u0f72\u0f42\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f7a\u0f51\u0f0d<\/span> \u201cEven though they\u2019re similar, they\u2019re not quite identical.\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f41\u0f7c\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f44\u0f74\u0f63\u0f0b\u0f61\u0f7c\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f7a\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f7a\u0f0d<\/span> <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f7a\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f66\u0fa4\u0fb1\u0f7c\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f4f\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f61\u0f7c\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f7a\u0f51\u0f0d<\/span> \u201cHe has money but he doesn\u2019t use it.\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f90\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f61\u0f42\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f7c\u0f0b\u0f60\u0f51\u0f74\u0f42\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f9f\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f5e\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f4f\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f60\u0f51\u0f74\u0f42<\/span> \u201cAlthough she has a nice voice, she doesn\u2019t sing.\u201d<\/li> <\/ul>","title":""}]}